alternatives.transcript: a sixty two year old male presenting for light headedness feeling faint shortness of breath feeling raspy wheezing and a flutter in his chest these symptoms come on with activity and have been popping up for the past two weeks with activity onset he says that it has disrupted majority of his daily activities and this is the first time this has ever happened to him he does say symptoms does only get relieved with rest patient has a past medical history of hypertension diagnosed ten years ago he also had a catheterization one year ago due to an abnormal ekg patient denies getting an echo done before in his life the patient is prescribed lisinopril ten milligrams that he takes for his hypertension and also reports taking a multivitamin patient has no known drug allergies no previous surgeries or hospitalizations immunizations up to date past medical family history is that his mother died of age at age forty due to a sudden cardiac death and father died at age sixty nine due to an early mi patient denies any illicit drug use tobacco or alcohol use patient reports that before symptom onset would exercise three to four times a week for forty five to sixty minutes at a time he is sexually active because and he is married with one partner and they live together and he also is a school teacher for seventh grade patient is positive for fatigue palpitations presyncope wheezing dyspnea and light headedness slash dizziness upon a vital review his vitals showed a heart rate of one hundred and ten blood pressure of one thirty over ninety and also o two sat of ninety six his physical exam revealed jugular venous distension a laterally displaced pmi wheezing and plus one bilateral lower extremity pitting edema labs revealed troponin and bnp to be within normal limits along with the rest of the panels the chest x-ray reveals cardiomegaly an echo revealed an ejection fraction of sixty percent along with left ventricular asymmetry and the thickening of the septum and the ekg revealed a normal sinus rhythm with left ventricular hypertrophy and tall r waves in the septal leads so mr palmer was diagnosed with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with a new york scale of three due to his inability to maintain majority of his normal activities patient was admitted to telemetry and activity as tolerated nurse intervention orders were strict i's and o's daily weights dvt prophylaxis o two nasal cannula and to maintain oxygen sats above ninety six percent he was also ordered a regular diet and for ivs to be kvo he was discontinued on lisinopril and has now been prescribed disopuramide one hundred milligrams per oral we sent referral to a cardio interventional cardiologist for aicd placement assessment as well as the cardiothoracic surgeon for assessment for a septomyectomy or alcohol injection patient reports having financial stability and insurance to proceed to the hospital for care and has a strong social and emotional support at home and we reported that upon discharge from the hospital to maintain healthy diet habits physical activity and to refrain from strenuous activity until a physician clears and gives the okay
